This panel will feature a pair of faculty members who have explored and responded to our changing climate through scholarship, creative work, and teaching.&#160;


Prof. Vince Eckhart (Biology) will discuss “how to do climate-change research without really trying.” Prof. Eckhart’s long-term field biology research with Grinnell students, originally motivated by other questions, connects increasingly to climate-change science. This may be the fate of any ecology research of sufficient length, as such studies uncover the signature of climate change and its consequences for natural systems.


Prof. Mirzam Pérez (Spanish) will share experiences from a new, interdisciplinary course she taught in fall 2024 titled Environmental Justice Art in Latino and Latin American Communities. Prof. Pérez’s students undertook creative projects and analyzed the historical, cultural, and political forces that shape environmental justice movements in Latinx and Latino contexts, focusing on Indigenous perspectives, colonial legacies, and contemporary struggles.&#160;


Please join us to learn from our colleagues’ insightful, valuable, and contrasting responses to climate change. Light refreshments will be served.

ZAWA!, the longest-standing&#160;professional flute duo of our time, enters its 27th season with a brand new program of works for two flutes and electronic media. Jill Felber and Claudia Anderson burst open the expressive possibilities of two flutes together starting in 1997, with Pulitzer Prize-winning composer Jennifer Higdon’s composition&#160;running the edgE.&#160;Jennifer’s dedication in the score, “to Jill and Claudia, always running the edge,”&#160;proved prophetic over the next 25 years. ZAWA!’s commissions, arrangements, and programs with strikingly diverse repertoire display drama, versatility and the humor the duo has become known for, all delivered with high-spirited energy and impact. Their new program includes enticing scores from composers both known and emerging, and electronic versions of pieces from earlier repertoire.&#160;


&#160;


&#160;ZAWA’s program includes Snap! &#160;for two C flutes and electronic media by Claudia’s music department colleague &#160;John Rommereim.&#160;

